          "body": "The chapter's most kinetic and celebrated passage begins with two exclamations: 'Listen! Behold!' (2:8). The beloved is coming — but not strolling; he is leaping over mountains and bounding over hills (2:8). The gazelle-and-young-stag simile (2:9) captures his wild, exuberant energy. Yet when he arrives, he stops at the wall, standing behind it, gazing through the windows, peering through the lattice (2:9). The restraint at the boundary is as telling as the energy of the approach. He does not breach the threshold uninvited; he positions himself at it and looks. Then he speaks (2:10-13), and his speech is the chapter's longest sustained lyric — a full spring inventory in service of a single invitation: arise, come with me. Winter is past (2:11); rain is over (2:11); flowers have appeared (2:12); the turtledove sings (2:12); the fig ripens (2:13); the vines give fragrance (2:13). He does not merely say 'Come.' He argues from creation: every sign of preparation is complete. The season of love has arrived. And then he repeats the invitation (2:13), more urgently the second time. Calvin noted that the beloved uses the whole of creation as his argument for the beloved's coming — there is a patience and an attentiveness to timing in his pursuit that is itself a form of love."
