          "body": "Verse 14 introduces the chapter's most intimate portrait of the woman: a dove hidden in the clefts of a rock, in the secret places of a steep cliff-face (2:14). The dove is beautiful, but concealed — her beauty is available only to the one who knows where to look. The beloved asks for two things: to see her form and to hear her voice. Both senses — sight and hearing — are engaged; her voice is as precious to him as her appearance. The verse is a portrait of someone who is lovely but somewhat hidden, needing to be invited out of the crevice of self-protection or modesty into full presence. Verse 15 then pivots sharply to a warning: catch the little foxes that ruin the vineyards — our vineyards, which are in blossom (2:15). The shift from the dove-image to the fox-warning is jarring in tone and has been debated across the interpretive tradition. Most commentators (Carr, Longman, Garrett) read 2:15 as an interlude in which both lovers — or perhaps the woman alone — name the threats to the relationship at its most fragile, fragrant stage. The little foxes are not the major catastrophes that destroy relationships suddenly; they are the small, incremental threats — neglect, irritation, divided attention, small dishonesties — that burrow under the roots of what is in bloom and ruin it from beneath."
